Task 1: The Problem (Data Loss)
Run PostgreSQL
docker run -d \
--name postgres-db \
-e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=admin123 \
postgres
Enter Container
docker exec -it postgres-db psql -U postgres
Create Data
CREATE TABLE students(
id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
name VARCHAR(50)
);

INSERT INTO students(name)
VALUES('Raja');

SELECT * FROM students;

Output:

 id | name
----+------
 1  | Raja
Remove Container
docker stop postgres-db
docker rm postgres-db
Create New Container
docker run -d \
--name postgres-db-new \
-e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=admin123 \
postgres
Check Data
docker exec -it postgres-db-new psql -U postgres
SELECT * FROM students;

You will get:

ERROR: relation "students" does not exist
Why?

Containers are ephemeral.

When a container is removed:

Container filesystem is deleted
Database files are deleted
Data is lost
Task 2: Named Volumes
Create Volume
docker volume create postgres-data
Verify
docker volume ls
Run Postgres with Volume
docker run -d \
--name postgres-db \
-e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=admin123 \
-v postgres-data:/var/lib/postgresql/data \
postgres
Add Data
docker exec -it postgres-db psql -U postgres
CREATE TABLE students(
id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
name VARCHAR(50)
);

INSERT INTO students(name)
VALUES('Raja');
Remove Container
docker stop postgres-db
docker rm postgres-db
Run New Container Using Same Volume
docker run -d \
--name postgres-db-new \
-e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=admin123 \
-v postgres-data:/var/lib/postgresql/data \
postgres
Verify Data
docker exec -it postgres-db-new psql -U postgres
SELECT * FROM students;

Output:

 id | name
----+------
 1  | Raja

Data survives because it is stored in the volume.

Inspect Volume
docker volume ls
docker volume inspect postgres-data
Task 3: Bind Mounts
Create Folder
mkdir mysite
cd mysite
Create HTML File
vim index.html
<h1>Hello Docker Bind Mount</h1>
Run Nginx
docker run -d \
--name nginx-bind \
-p 8080:80 \
-v $(pwd):/usr/share/nginx/html \
nginx

Open:

http://localhost:8080

You will see:

Hello Docker Bind Mount
Edit File
vim index.html
<h1>Updated Website</h1>

Refresh browser.

Changes appear instantly.

Named Volume vs Bind Mount
Named Volume	Bind Mount
Managed by Docker	Managed by Host OS
Stored in Docker area	Stored anywhere on host
Best for databases	Best for source code
Portable	Host dependent
More secure	Full host access
Task 4: Docker Networking Basics
List Networks
docker network ls

Output similar:

bridge
host
none
Inspect Bridge Network
docker network inspect bridge
Run Containers
docker run -dit --name c1 ubuntu
docker run -dit --name c2 ubuntu
Install Ping
docker exec -it c1 bash
apt update
apt install iputils-ping -y

Do same for c2.

Ping by Name
ping c2

Result:

ping: c2: Name or service not known

Fails.

Get IP
docker inspect c2

Find:

172.17.0.x
Ping by IP
ping 172.17.0.x

Works.

Task 5: Custom Networks
Create Network
docker network create my-app-net
Run Containers
docker run -dit --name app1 --network my-app-net ubuntu
docker run -dit --name app2 --network my-app-net ubuntu
Install Ping
docker exec -it app1 bash
apt update && apt install iputils-ping -y
Ping by Name
ping app2

Output:

PING app2 (172.18.0.x)

Works.

Why Does Custom Network Work?

Docker creates an internal DNS server for user-defined networks.

When a container asks:

app2

Docker DNS resolves:

app2 → 172.18.0.x

The default bridge network does not automatically provide this name resolution.

Task 6: Put Everything Together
Create Network
docker network create my-app-net
Create Volume
docker volume create pg-data
Run Database
docker run -d \
--name postgres-db \
--network my-app-net \
-e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=admin123 \
-v pg-data:/var/lib/postgresql/data \
postgres
Run App Container
docker run -dit \
--name app \
--network my-app-net \
ubuntu
Enter App
docker exec -it app bash
Install Networking Tools
apt update
apt install iputils-ping -y
Test Connectivity
ping postgres-db

Output:

PING postgres-db (172.18.0.x)

Success.

The application container can now communicate with the database using the container name:

Host = postgres-db
Port = 5432
